The man who ran TV shows and casinos that churned out winners was poised to star on the biggest political stage on earth, with the intrigue straight out of Citizen Kane.
Like a rock star, he lapped up the admiration, thrived on the highs that hero-worship engendered, played to the gallery, who in turn forgave his indiscretions, ignored the insults, for their hero could do no wrong.



