Wisconsin Supreme Court Justice Jill Karofsky expressed it best when she castigated one of Trump’s lawyers: “What you want is for us to overturn this election so that your king can stay in power. That is so un-American.” The pathological desire to cling to power is something we tend to associate with dictators in South America, Africa and Asia.
It is entirely within character that having gone missing in action at the height of the pandemic, having treated the threat to health and lives with a cavalier attitude that has seen 300,000 dead, Trump now sits in front of the cameras taking credit for the great scientific achievement of new-fangled vaccines, with not a hint of irony.
Gaining ground
Mastering his media savvy, Trump orchestrated a significant shift in the American consciousness. He successfully tapped into the disaffection that had gradually seeped into the population.
Across Europe, the conservative, right-wing discourse was gaining ground. The UK had turned its back on the EU, trotting out an anti-immigrant, reclaim our sovereignty narrative that split the country right down the middle.



